ewspaper article, illustrates some of the differences between
uxemburgish and Standard German as it is used in Luxem-
urg. These differences, which are lexical, grammatical and
onological, demonstrate the nature of the difficulties faced
Luxembourg children in school:
emburgish:
Véi de Rodange 1872 säi Buch drécke gelooss huet, du bluf hien drop
1. En hat e puer Leit ze luusség op d'Zéiwe getrëppelt, déi dat net verquësst
Eréischt eng Generation doerno huet de Rodange ugefaang séng giedléch
e kréien. Séng Kanner hu wéinstens nach erlieft, wéi 1927 eng Grimmel
eem gutt gemaach guf, wat un him verbrach gi wor!
ard German:
Rodange 1872 sein Buch drucken liess, hatte er keinen Erfolg damit.
riel List war er ein paar Leuten auf die Zehen getreten, und die konnten
nicht verzeihen. Erst eine Generation später begann Rodange, seinen
tehenden Platz zu erhalten. Seine Kinder haben es wenigstens noch
asS1927 ein wenig von dem gut gemacht wurde, was an ihm verbrochen
var!
n Rodange had his book printed in 1872 he had no success with
too much intrigue he had trodden on some people's toes, and
d not forgive him that. Only a generation later did Rodange
receive his rightful place. His children at least experienced the
od, in 1927, of some of the wrong that had been done him.
Stable are diglossic situations? Interesting light is shed
duestion by what has happened recently in the case of
